The three common tasks in posterior analysis are posterior estimation, posterior hypothesis testing, and posterior prediction.

Exercise 8.2

A drawback to reporting only the central tendency is that it makes posteriors with very different levels of confidence/certainty seem like they’re the same; including a measure of spread lets us see how precise our posterior is.

Exercise 8.4

Part A

Posterior odds are our updated understanding of a parameter; basically, how much more (or less) likely that parameter is to be against the null vs. with the null, based on our updated posterior model.

Part B

Prior odds are the initial understanding of a parameter; the same as the above, but based on the prior model.

Part C

The Bayes Factor essentially tells us how much more confident we are in our posterior vs. our prior. You might want to calculate it to see how convincing your findings are.

Exercise 8.5

Part A

Posterior predictive models incorporate uncertainty about both sampling variability (the actual value of the sample statistic in whatever sample we happen to get, which could be anywhere around the actual parameter) and posterior variability (the fact that our most likely estimate for the parameter isn’t the only possible value of the parameter).

Part B

You’ve done a few polls in a county for your candidate, and you want to predict how many voters in that county will vote for them in the election to see if it’s enough to flip the state in your favor.

Part C

Both! Posterior predictive model is… \[ f(y'|y) = \int f(y'|\pi)f(\pi|y)d\pi \] …where y is the data and \(\pi\) is the parameter.

Exercise 8.8

Part A

set.seed(18)
dist88 <- rgamma(100000, shape=1, rate=5)
hdi1 <- as.vector(hdi(dist88, .width=.95))

plot_gamma(1,5) +
  stat_function(fun = dgamma, 
                  args = list(1, 5), 
                  xlim = hdi1, 
                  geom = "area", 
                  fill = "lightblue") +
  geom_segment(aes(x=mean(dist88), xend=mean(dist88), y=0, 
                   yend=dgamma(mean(dist88), 1, 5)))

Part B

ci1 <- qgamma(c(.025, .975), 1, 5)
summarize_gamma(1,5)
##   mean mode  var  sd
## 1  0.2    0 0.04 0.2
mean <- .2
plot_gamma(1,5) +
  stat_function(fun = dgamma, 
                  args = list(1, 5), 
                  xlim = ci1, 
                  geom = "area", 
                  fill = "lightblue") +
  geom_segment(aes(x=mean, xend=mean, y=0, 
                   yend=dgamma(mean, 1, 5)))

Part C

These two intervals are not the same. The one in Part A is shifted slightly to the left; this is because the Gamma(1,5) distribution is highly skewed right. In this case, I think that the HDI is more appropriate, because it captures the mode better than the CI.

Part D

Exercise 8.9

Part A

post_prob89 <- pbeta(.4, 4, 3, lower.tail=FALSE)
post_prob89
## [1] 0.8208

Part B

post_odds89 <- post_prob89 / (1 - post_prob89)
post_odds89
## [1] 4.580357

It’s about 4.5 times as likely that pi > .4 than that pi ≤ .4 based on the posterior model.

Part C

prior_prob89 <- pbeta(0.4, 1, .8, lower.tail = FALSE)
prior_odds89 <- prior_prob89 / (1-prior_prob89)
prior_odds89
## [1] 1.98098

It’s about 2 times as likely that pi > .4 than that pi ≤ .4 based on the prior model.

Part D

bf89 <- post_odds89 / prior_odds89
bf89
## [1] 2.312168

We’re about twice as confident in our answer now as we were before.

Part E

Through our analysis, we’re pretty sure that pi > .4, because this is the most plausible answer by a factor of 4.5. Our data helped us by doubling our confidence in our final analysis.

Exercise 8.10

Part A

post_prob810 <- pnorm(5.2, 5, 3)
post_prob810
## [1] 0.5265765

Part B

post_odds810 <- post_prob810 / (1 - post_prob810)
post_odds810
## [1] 1.112274

There’s a slightly greater chance that mu < 5.2 than that mu ≥ 5.2.

Part C

prior_prob810 <- pnorm(5.2, 10, 10)
prior_odds810 <- prior_prob810 / (1 - prior_prob810)
prior_odds810
## [1] 0.4611631

It’s about twice as likely that mu ≥ 5.2 than that mu < 5.2. (or…It’s about half as likely that mu < 5.2 than that mu ≥ 5.2.)

Part D

bf810 <- post_odds810 / prior_odds810
bf810
## [1] 2.411888

We’re about 2.5 times more confident in our model now than we were before.

Part E

Even though our data helped us build a model that we’re much more confident in, it’s essentially equally plausible that mu < 5.2 or that mu ≥ 5.2, so we can’t make a definitive statement on our hypotheses.

Exercise 8.15

Part A

The credible interval from above is (.129, .173) which means that plausible guesses for the proportion of adults that don’t believe in climate change are between 12.9% and 17.3%. This makes me pretty confident that more than 10% of people don’t believe in climate change - although a proportion of at or below .1 is definitely possible, it’s not very likely.

Part B

pbeta(.1, 151, 852, lower.tail = FALSE)
## [1] 0.9999997

The posterior probability of p > .1 is essentially 1; based on our updated knowledge, it is almost certain that at least 10% of people don’t believe in climate change.

Part C

post_prob815 <- .9999997
post_odds815 <- post_prob815 / (1 - post_prob815)
prior_prob815 <- pbeta(.1, 1, 2, lower.tail = FALSE)
prior_odds815 <- prior_prob815 / (1 - prior_prob815)
bf815 <- post_odds815 / prior_odds815
bf815
## [1] 781892.8

We are tens of thousands of times more confident in our analysis now than we were in our prior model. Cool !

Part D

I can confidently say that pi is greater than .1.

Part B

mcmc_trace(sim816, pars="pi")

The trace plots look good! There’s no places where it gets “stuck” and no clear trend up or down, which means it’s mixing fast enough.

mcmc_dens_overlay(sim816, pars = "pi")

The density plots look good - it looks like the most likely value for pi is around .15.

mcmc_acf(sim816, pars = "pi")

The autocorrelation for all four chains essentially disappears after a lag of 5, which is good because we can assume that it approximates an independent sample.

Part C

neff_ratio(sim816, pars = "pi")
## [1] 0.3645845

An effective sample size ration of .36 means that this simulation is as effective as an independent sample of 36% of the size. This is an ok number.

rhat(sim816, pars = "pi")
## [1] 1.000031

The R-hat value is below 1.05, which is good: it means that the variance across all of the chains is equal to the variance inside one chain.

Part B

mcmc_trace(sim823, pars = "lambda")

mcmc_dens_overlay(sim823, pars = "lambda")

mcmc_acf(sim823, pars = "lambda")

neff_ratio(sim823, pars = "lambda")
## [1] 0.3835165
rhat(sim823, pars = "lambda")
## [1] 1.000036

Trace plots look normal with no sticking points or obvious trends; density plots look similar across chains and point to a lambda of 1.5; autocorrelation drops to essentially 0 after a lag of 5, which is good; effective sample size ratio is .38, which is normal; and rhat is well below the 1.05 mark of concern. Overall, looks good!

Part B

The most likely number of loons is 1; the distribution of possible loons is skewed to the right, so it is possible to see 6 or even 7 loons (though not likely).

Part C

loondf |>

  tabyl(loontest)
##  loontest     n percent
##     FALSE 31224  0.7806

There’s a 22.3% chance that an observer will see no loons in the next observation period.
